explain: I work with teachers on daily basis discussing content and sometimes instruction.

I do note feel that I am a math coach in my building. Nor, do I feel that I would be able to have open conversations with the other teachers about instructional practices. In order for this to occur, my principal would need to initiate and follow-up with this expectation.

As I am not officially a coach, I feel as though I haven't been able to put many of these concepts into practice.  That being said, I feel that my instructional practices have improved dramatically because of my deeper understanding of content knowledge and the standards of mathematical practices.  I am continuing to push myself and strive for better every week.
I have loved talking math with other staff.  I have a chance to lead a professional development day that I am excited to share
I have been working closely with the other kindergarten teacher to model how to do the Eureka math.
I am a regular education teacher.
I am in a regular classroom, and do not have a lot of time available to do the coaching.

It is difficult to apply these skills because I am a curriculum leader, not a math coach.  I do not have authority over anyone nor the ability to make decisions that impact others.  I can simply lead by example and have professional discussions with my colleagues.

It has been a slow process as teachers are not always willing to discuss math content knowledge. I think they are more concerned with the data they are collecting at this point, rather than using the data to inform instruction.
I am not working as a math coach. I use the knowledge that I've gained to inform my own practices and my discussions with colleagues.
I am a regular classroom teacher. I have not assumed a "coaching" role at this point in the process.
I haven't had the opportunity to apply official math coaching knowledge as of yet.  I am preparing to do a math coaching observation with a colleague for our field experience currently.
I am a math intervention teacher and I work with students mainly but at times I work with teachers co teaching, preparing their lesson and helping them develop the lesson as well.

I am  not a math coach, I am an instructional teacher.  I using what I am learning in my own classroom.  Up to this point, I find that I am using this time to reflect more on my own knowledge and practices.
It has been a slow process but I have been able to share with colleagues.
I have just completed my first college math class in 14 years of teaching.

Although I am not an official math coach, I am learning valuable knowledge that can be implemented in my own classroom, and also shared with my colleagues and administration.  I am also realizing that I have tons to learn.

I have been asked by administration to work closely with another 3rd grade teacher to help him become a better, more successful math teacher. He brings his entire class of students into my classroom for the concept development portion of the lesson. Here we work together to assist the students in their understanding of the content.
I am not a math coach. I use the skills that I am acquiring in my class and take them back to my administration to enhance instruction in our building and district.
I am not in a coaching position, but applying pedagogy and content knowledge to work with math colleagues in designing curriculum, instruction and assessment

I feel that I have made significant progress in this area. I think my biggest gain is simply with confidence. I'm getting great ideas from presenters and colleagues during the courses and the coaching sessions, but I'm also seeing that I am using and have been using many of the principles to action in terms of my teaching.
I am not in a coaching position.  I have not had the opportunity to act as a coach with my colleagues outside of the activities from our classes and coaching meetings.

I have had discussions about identifying and using appropriate math tasks with students to support student learning and overall outcomes for open ended thinking.  We are reviewing tasks to support lessons.
I am not currently a math coach, but I am using new information on a regular basis with my grade level team.
I am currently a math teacher, not a coach. However, I share my content knowledge and expertise with the interested colleagues during our department meetings or common planning periods.
I believe I have become more competent in my coaching and pedagogy since the beginning.

I have had the opportunity to observe and be observed by colleagues/coaches. I frequently communicate with my current math coach, and we co-teach when we can. I do my best to share my math learning, content knowledge, and pedagogy with colleagues at PLC's or grade level meetings where I act as my 5th grade grade level chair.
